In this study we choose: income rate, population per km, average life expectancy, and suicide rate per 100k¶

Unfortunately, the data for the suicde rate per 100k in the gapmineder website is missing alot of data, thus we will have to get it manualy through the total population dataset and the total suicide deaths¶

#found the code for this part here :https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/find-elements-present-first-array-not-second/
def findMissing(a, b, n, m): 
    dof=[]
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(m): 
            if (a[i] == b[j]): 
                break
  
        if (j == m - 1): 
            dof.append(a[i])
    return(dof)
            
a=df_income['country'].unique()  
b=df_lifex['country'].unique()
l_of_a = len(a) 
l_of_b = len(b) 
income_life=findMissing(a, b, l_of_a, l_of_b)

def continent(c):
    if c in Africa:
        return 'Africa'
    elif c in Asia:
        return 'Asia'
    elif c in Europe:
        return 'Europe'
    elif c in North_America:
        return 'North_America'
    elif c in South_America:
        return 'South_America'
    elif c in Australia_Oceania:
        return 'Australia_Oceania'

Conclusions¶

We can conclude that:¶

- The highest income continent is Europe followd by Asia, North America, South America, Australia/Oceania, and lastly Africa and the highest income coutnry is asian¶

-the lowest income countries have the lowest suicide rate -lower than 25% of the average income rate- followed by the lower 50% average income rate, but in case of the Countries above 75% of the average income rate and Countries below 75% of the average income rate it isn't quite obvious. Of course, This does not mean that higher income rate is directly correlated to higher suicide rate but it's an indication that these countries have some problems that needs to be fixed¶

-the higher income countries tend to have higher population per km, although the relation is not strong¶

-There is no colleration between higher income rate and average life expectany¶

-There is also no colleration continent and average life expectany¶

limitations:¶

The data that has been used was provided by gapminder and may have some inaccuracies.¶

The results shown do not mean that one correletion is the result of another, but rather an indicator of the problem in these group of countries since the factors and variables are alot and one can not generalize such outcome as a causation¶

We would have liked to do more analysis and try to find relationships between countries in certain groups (ex: what is common in countries with higher income rate) but unfortunately due to the lack and limitaion of the data, we are not able to do that.¶
